{"title_page": "Alvarez Guitars", "text_new": "{{Advert|date=November 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox company/wikidata\n| name             = Alvarez Guitars\n| logo             = Alvarez guitars logo.png\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type             = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry         = [[Musical instrument]]\n| founder          = Kazuo Yairi\n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| products         = {{nowrap|\n* [[Acoustic guitar]]s <br>([[Steel-string acoustic guitar|steel-string]], [[classical guitar|classical]])\n* [[Ukulele]]s\n* Accessories\n}}\n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = over 750 world wide\n| parent           = [[St. Louis Music]] \n| divisions        =\n| subsid           = \n| footnotes        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|1965}}\n| location_city    = [[St. Louis, Missouri]] \n| location_country = United States\n| location         = <!-- this parameter modifies \"Headquarters\" -->\n| origins          = \n| slogan   = \n| homepage         = [https://www.alvarezguitars.com/ alvarezguitars.com]\n| dissolved        = \n}}\n\n'''Alvarez''' is a [[guitar]] brand founded in 1965 by owner and distributor [[St. Louis Music]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmtonline.co.uk/blog/2018/11/07/history-of-alvarez-guitars-why-are-they-so-good/|title=History Of Alvarez Guitars \u2013 Why Are They So Good?|date=2018-11-07|website=PMT Online|language=en|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref> Alvarez manufactures [[Steel-string acoustic guitar|steel-string]] and [[classical guitar|classical]] guitars, [[ukulele]]s and, for a time, solid and hollow-body electric guitars and basses.\n\n== History ==\nIn the late 1960\u2019s, St. Louis Music's founder, Gene Kornblum, met [[Kazuo Yairi]], a Master Luthier in Japan who produced handmade concert classical guitars. Together, St. Louis Music and the Yairi factory started to design and develop steel string acoustic guitars and imported them into the [[United States]]. The guitars took the brand name of St. Louis Music's Spanish guitar line \u201cAlvarez\u201d. Similar instruments were also sold under the factory brand of \u201cK. Yairi\u201d in Europe and other parts of the world.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmtonline.co.uk/blog/2018/11/07/history-of-alvarez-guitars-why-are-they-so-good/|title=History Of Alvarez Guitars \u2013 Why Are They So Good?|date=2018-11-07|website=PMT Online|language=en|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2005 to 2009, the brand was owned by [[LOUD Technologies]], which also owns [[Mackie]], [[Ampeg]], [[LOUD Technologies|Crate]] and other music-related brands. In 2009, Mark Ragin (owner of US Band & Orchestra and St. Louis Music) brought the management and distribution of the guitars back to St. Louis Music. As early as 2011, SLM senior vice president [[Chris Meikle]] has acted as Alvarez head of development<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://onlinedigeditions.com/article/People/3135368/513329/article.html|title=People|website=onlinedigeditions.com|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>, overseeing the redesign of Artist Series and other models<ref>{{cite web|url=http://viewer.zmags.com/publication/45ec2226#/45ec2226/177|title=MSR 2013-Q4|website=Viewer.zmags.com|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref>and rolling out new instrument lines such as the 2014 Masterworks Series, <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierguitar.com/blogs/5-daily-news/post/20151-alvarez-announces-masterworks-series|title=Alvarez Announces Masterworks Series|website=Premierguitar.com|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref> the Alvarez 50th anniversary 1965 Series<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acousticguitar.com/NAMM-Sessions/Winter-NAMM-2015-Alvarez-Celebrates-50-Years-in-the-Guitar-Business|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711174644/http://www.acousticguitar.com/NAMM-Sessions/Winter-NAMM-2015-Alvarez-Celebrates-50-Years-in-the-Guitar-Business|archivedate=2015-07-11|url-status=dead|accessdate=2015-07-11}}</ref>, Alvarez-Yairi Honduran Series<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acousticguitar.com/alvarez-winter-namm-2018/|website=acousticguitar.com|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref> and the Grateful Dead Series.\n\nWhile many of its models are produced in [[China]], the top-tier Alvarez-Yairi instruments are handmade at the [[Yairi]] factory in [[Kani, Gifu]]-[[Japan]], part of the legacy of Kazuo Yairi, the late master luthier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alvarezguitars.com/about/history/|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151209032411/http://alvarezguitars.com/about/history/|archive-date=2015-12-09|url-status=dead|access-date=2015-07-11}}</ref> Every Alvarez guitar undergoes a full set up and inspection in their guitar shop in [[St. Louis|St. Louis, Missouri]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://masonmusicstudios.com/best-acoustic-guitars-400/|title=Best Acoustic Guitars Under $400|date=2017-02-13|website=Mason Music|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>\n\n== Series ==\nAlvarez Guitars manufactures many models of guitar which are categorized by price point and specialty into series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hmtrad.com/collections/alvarez|title=Alvarez|website=House of Musical Traditions|language=en|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Regent Series ===\nAlvarez considers Regent Series a high quality entry-level line of guitars designed to give younger players and players new to the instrument a positive learning experience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/instruments/regent-series/|title=Regent Series|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> In 2018 Alvarez released the Regent School Series designed specifically for students. The nut width is slimmer than the standard size and the neck has been custom shaped to be comfortable for smaller hands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlouismusic.com/alvarez-introduces-regent-school-series/|title=Alvarez Introduces Regent School Series|date=2018-03-07|website=St. Louis Music|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Artist Series ===\n\nAlvarez has stated that its goal with Artist Series is to deliver pro level guitars at excellent value through the close attention to detail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/instruments/artist-series/|title=Artist Series|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>Alvarez Artist Series has won several awards, including a 5/5 rating in [[Acoustic Guitar (magazine)|Acoustic Guitar Magazine]] and a nomination for best guitar series from [[The Music and Sound Retailer.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/the-wonder-wall/|title=The Wonder Wall|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>In 2017 Artist Series began adding new key features and models including armrests <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/alvarez-debuts-new-armrest-models-artist-series/|title=Alvarez Debuts New Armrest Models for Artist Series|date=2017-01-20|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>, travel guitars like the Delta DeLite and LJ2<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/alvarez-unveils-ultra-compact-delta-delite/|title=Alvarez Unveils the Ultra Compact Delta DeLite|date=2017-01-21|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>, and ATR (Advanced Tonal Response) system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/alvarez-implements-atr-advanced-tonal-response-system/|title=Alvarez Implements ATR\u2122 (Advanced Tonal Response) System|date=2017-02-15|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Masterworks Series ===\n[[File:MPA66SHB Alvarez.jpg|thumb|An Alvarez Masterworks Series Parlor Guitar with shadowburst finish and inlays]]\nIn 2014 Alvarez introduced the Masterworks Series featuring all solid wood construction and high end appointments such as gold tuners, ebony bridge pins, mother of pearl inlays and maple or koa binding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premierguitar.com/blogs/5-daily-news/post/20151-alvarez-announces-masterworks-series|title=Alvarez Announces Masterworks Series|website=www.premierguitar.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> In 2019 Alvarez introduced bluegrass focused Masterworks models, the MF60OM and the MD60BG, that feature construction that emphasizes response when playing with a plectrum and [[flatpicking]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlouismusic.com/alvarez-now-shipping-masterworks-bluegrass-model-md60bg/|title=Alvarez Now Shipping Masterworks Bluegrass Model MD60BG|date=2018-11-05|website=St. Louis Music|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Alvarez-Yairi Series ===\n[[File:1-Alvarez-Yairi-Masterworks-DYMR70SB-Guitar-Giveaway.jpg|thumb|Alvarez Yairi Dreadnought DYM70SB]]\nAlvarez Yairi guitars are a\\ handmade flagship series, crafted in the Yairi factory in [[Kani, Gifu|Kani, Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/instruments/yairi-series/|title=Yairi Series|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>Alvarez Yairi have been the guitar of choice for many professional touring musicians including [[Jerry Garcia]], [[Bob Weir|Bob Wier]], [[Ani DiFranco]], and [[Joe Bonamassa]].<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmtonline.co.uk/blog/2018/11/07/history-of-alvarez-guitars-why-are-they-so-good/|title=History Of Alvarez Guitars \u2013 Why Are They So Good?|date=2018-11-07|website=PMT Online|language=en|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>Alvarez Yairi take the name of master luthier [[Kazuo Yairi]](1932-2014) who partnered with St. Louis Music in the late 1960's to bring Alvarez Guitars to the market.<ref name=\":03\" />Kazuo Yairi inspired many innovations that are still used in Alvarez guitars today, including the Direct Coupled Bridge, careful selection of tonewoods, and manual carving; a practice that he referred to as \"listening with your hands\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/10724817/Kazuo-Yairi-obituary.html|title=Kazuo Yairi - obituary|journal=Daily Telegraph|date=2014-03-26|access-date=2019-06-18|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>In 2017 the Alvarez team discovered a lost cache of Honduran Mahogany that Kazuo Yairi had purchased and stored on a plot of land near his factory in the mid 1970s.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/alvarez-introduces-new-honduran-mahogany-yairi-guitars/|title=Alvarez Introduces New Honduran Mahogany Yairi Guitars|date=2018-04-01|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>Tonewood that has been naturally seasoning for this amount of time is coveted by luthiers around the world, and this discovery led to the release of the Yairi Honduran line of guitars which debuted in 2018.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Alvarez Artists Past & Present==\n{{Unreferenced|section|date=December 2017}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Jerry Garcia]]\n*[[Raulin Rodriguez]]\n*[[Antony Santos]]\n*[[Devin Townsend]]\n*[[Bob Weir]]\n*[[Carlos Santana]]\n*[[Harry Chapin]]\n*[[Glen Hansard]]\n*[[Ani DiFranco]]\n*[[David Crosby]]\n*[[Graham Nash]]\n*Roy Muniz\n*[[Jon Anderson]]\n*[[Pete Yorn]]\n*[[Jeff Young]]\n*[[Joe Bonamassa]]\n*[[Shaun Morgan]]\n*[[Josh Turner]]\n*[[Monte Montgomery]]\n*[[Mike Inez]]\n*[[Miguel Dakota]]\n*[[Viktor Tsoi]]\n*Rick Droit\n*[[Mason Ramsey]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last= |first= |title= Acoustic Guitars: The Illustrated Encyclopedia |location= New York |publisher= Chartwell Books |date = 2011 |pages =  |format= |isbn= 978-0-7858-3571-4}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alvarez Guitars}}\n*{{Official website|http://alvarezguitars.com}}\n\n{{Guitar brands}}\n\n[[Category:Guitar manufacturing companies of the United States|Alvarez Guitars]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in St. Louis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Advert|date=November 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox company/wikidata\n| name             = Alvarez Guitars\n| logo             = Alvarez guitars logo.png\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type             = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry         = [[Musical instrument]]\n| founder          = Kazuo Yairi\n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| products         = {{nowrap|\n* [[Acoustic guitar]]s <br>([[Steel-string acoustic guitar|steel-string]], [[classical guitar|classical]])\n* [[Ukulele]]s\n* Accessories\n}}\n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = over 750 world wide\n| parent           = [[St. Louis Music]] \n| divisions        =\n| subsid           = \n| footnotes        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|1965}}\n| location_city    = [[St. Louis, Missouri]] \n| location_country = United States\n| location         = <!-- this parameter modifies \"Headquarters\" -->\n| origins          = \n| slogan   = \n| homepage         = [https://www.alvarezguitars.com/ alvarezguitars.com]\n| dissolved        = \n}}\n\n'''Alvarez''' is a [[guitar]] brand founded in 1965 by owner and distributor [[St. Louis Music]]<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmtonline.co.uk/blog/2018/11/07/history-of-alvarez-guitars-why-are-they-so-good/|title=History Of Alvarez Guitars \u2013 Why Are They So Good?|date=2018-11-07|website=PMT Online|language=en|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>. Alvarez manufactures [[Steel-string acoustic guitar|steel-string]] and [[classical guitar|classical]] guitars, [[ukulele]]s and, for a time, solid and hollow-body electric guitars and basses.\n\n== History ==\nIn the late 1960\u2019s, St. Louis Music's founder, Gene Kornblum, met [[Kazuo Yairi]], a Master Luthier in Japan who produced handmade concert classical guitars. Together, St. Louis Music and the Yairi factory started to design and develop steel string acoustic guitars and imported them into the [[United States]]. The guitars took the brand name of St. Louis Music's Spanish guitar line \u201cAlvarez\u201d. Similar instruments were also sold under the factory brand of \u201cK. Yairi\u201d in Europe and other parts of the world.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmtonline.co.uk/blog/2018/11/07/history-of-alvarez-guitars-why-are-they-so-good/|title=History Of Alvarez Guitars \u2013 Why Are They So Good?|date=2018-11-07|website=PMT Online|language=en|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2005 to 2009, the brand was owned by [[LOUD Technologies]], which also owns [[Mackie]], [[Ampeg]], [[LOUD Technologies|Crate]] and other music-related brands. In 2009, Mark Ragin (owner of US Band & Orchestra and St. Louis Music) brought the management and distribution of the guitars back to St. Louis Music. As early as 2011, SLM senior vice president [[Chris Meikle]] has acted as Alvarez head of development<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://onlinedigeditions.com/article/People/3135368/513329/article.html|title=People|website=onlinedigeditions.com|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>, overseeing the redesign of Artist Series and other models<ref>{{cite web|url=http://viewer.zmags.com/publication/45ec2226#/45ec2226/177|title=MSR 2013-Q4|website=Viewer.zmags.com|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref>and rolling out new instrument lines such as the 2014 Masterworks Series, <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierguitar.com/blogs/5-daily-news/post/20151-alvarez-announces-masterworks-series|title=Alvarez Announces Masterworks Series|website=Premierguitar.com|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref> the Alvarez 50th anniversary 1965 Series<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acousticguitar.com/NAMM-Sessions/Winter-NAMM-2015-Alvarez-Celebrates-50-Years-in-the-Guitar-Business|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711174644/http://www.acousticguitar.com/NAMM-Sessions/Winter-NAMM-2015-Alvarez-Celebrates-50-Years-in-the-Guitar-Business|archivedate=2015-07-11|url-status=dead|accessdate=2015-07-11}}</ref>, Alvarez-Yairi Honduran Series<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acousticguitar.com/alvarez-winter-namm-2018/|website=acousticguitar.com|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref> and the Grateful Dead Series.\n\nWhile many of its models are produced in [[China]], the top-tier Alvarez-Yairi instruments are handmade at the [[Yairi]] factory in [[Kani, Gifu]]-[[Japan]], part of the legacy of Kazuo Yairi, the late master luthier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alvarezguitars.com/about/history/|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151209032411/http://alvarezguitars.com/about/history/|archive-date=2015-12-09|url-status=dead|access-date=2015-07-11}}</ref> Every Alvarez guitar undergoes a full set up and inspection in their guitar shop in [[St. Louis|St. Louis, Missouri]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://masonmusicstudios.com/best-acoustic-guitars-400/|title=Best Acoustic Guitars Under $400|date=2017-02-13|website=Mason Music|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>\n\n== Series ==\nAlvarez Guitars manufactures many models of guitar which are categorized by price point and specialty into series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hmtrad.com/collections/alvarez|title=Alvarez|website=House of Musical Traditions|language=en|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Regent Series ===\nAlvarez considers Regent Series a high quality entry-level line of guitars designed to give younger players and players new to the instrument a positive learning experience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/instruments/regent-series/|title=Regent Series|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> In 2018 Alvarez released the Regent School Series designed specifically for students. The nut width is slimmer than the standard size and the neck has been custom shaped to be comfortable for smaller hands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlouismusic.com/alvarez-introduces-regent-school-series/|title=Alvarez Introduces Regent School Series|date=2018-03-07|website=St. Louis Music|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Artist Series ===\n\nAlvarez has stated that its goal with Artist Series is to deliver pro level guitars at excellent value through the close attention to detail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/instruments/artist-series/|title=Artist Series|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>Alvarez Artist Series has won several awards, including a 5/5 rating in [[Acoustic Guitar (magazine)|Acoustic Guitar Magazine]] and a nomination for best guitar series from [[The Music and Sound Retailer.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/the-wonder-wall/|title=The Wonder Wall|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>In 2017 Artist Series began adding new key features and models including armrests <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/alvarez-debuts-new-armrest-models-artist-series/|title=Alvarez Debuts New Armrest Models for Artist Series|date=2017-01-20|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>, travel guitars like the Delta DeLite and LJ2<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/alvarez-unveils-ultra-compact-delta-delite/|title=Alvarez Unveils the Ultra Compact Delta DeLite|date=2017-01-21|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>, and ATR (Advanced Tonal Response) system<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/alvarez-implements-atr-advanced-tonal-response-system/|title=Alvarez Implements ATR\u2122 (Advanced Tonal Response) System|date=2017-02-15|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>.\n\n=== Masterworks Series ===\n[[File:MPA66SHB Alvarez.jpg|thumb|An Alvarez Masterworks Series Parlor Guitar with shadowburst finish and inlays]]\nIn 2014 Alvarez introduced the Masterworks Series featuring all solid wood construction and high end appointments such as gold tuners, ebony bridge pins, mother of pearl inlays and maple or koa binding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premierguitar.com/blogs/5-daily-news/post/20151-alvarez-announces-masterworks-series|title=Alvarez Announces Masterworks Series|website=www.premierguitar.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> In 2019 Alvarez introduced bluegrass focused Masterworks models, the MF60OM and the MD60BG, that feature construction that emphasizes response when playing with a plectrum and [[flatpicking]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlouismusic.com/alvarez-now-shipping-masterworks-bluegrass-model-md60bg/|title=Alvarez Now Shipping Masterworks Bluegrass Model MD60BG|date=2018-11-05|website=St. Louis Music|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Alvarez-Yairi Series ===\n[[File:1-Alvarez-Yairi-Masterworks-DYMR70SB-Guitar-Giveaway.jpg|thumb|Alvarez Yairi Dreadnought DYM70SB]]\nAlvarez Yairi guitars are a\\ handmade flagship series, crafted in the Yairi factory in [[Kani, Gifu|Kani, Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/instruments/yairi-series/|title=Yairi Series|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>Alvarez Yairi have been the guitar of choice for many professional touring musicians including [[Jerry Garcia]], [[Bob Weir|Bob Wier]], [[Ani DiFranco]], and [[Joe Bonamassa]].<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmtonline.co.uk/blog/2018/11/07/history-of-alvarez-guitars-why-are-they-so-good/|title=History Of Alvarez Guitars \u2013 Why Are They So Good?|date=2018-11-07|website=PMT Online|language=en|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>Alvarez Yairi take the name of master luthier [[Kazuo Yairi]](1932-2014) who partnered with St. Louis Music in the late 1960's to bring Alvarez Guitars to the market.<ref name=\":03\" />Kazuo Yairi inspired many innovations that are still used in Alvarez guitars today, including the Direct Coupled Bridge, careful selection of tonewoods, and manual carving; a practice that he referred to as \"listening with your hands\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/10724817/Kazuo-Yairi-obituary.html|title=Kazuo Yairi - obituary|journal=Daily Telegraph|date=2014-03-26|access-date=2019-06-18|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>In 2017 the Alvarez team discovered a lost cache of Honduran Mahogany that Kazuo Yairi had purchased and stored on a plot of land near his factory in the mid 1970s.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.alvarezguitars.com/alvarez-introduces-new-honduran-mahogany-yairi-guitars/|title=Alvarez Introduces New Honduran Mahogany Yairi Guitars|date=2018-04-01|website=Alvarez Guitars|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>Tonewood that has been naturally seasoning for this amount of time is coveted by luthiers around the world, and this discovery led to the release of the Yairi Honduran line of guitars which debuted in 2018.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Alvarez Artists Past & Present==\n{{Unreferenced|section|date=December 2017}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Jerry Garcia]]\n*[[Raulin Rodriguez]]\n*[[Antony Santos]]\n*[[Devin Townsend]]\n*[[Bob Weir]]\n*[[Carlos Santana]]\n*[[Harry Chapin]]\n*[[Glen Hansard]]\n*[[Ani DiFranco]]\n*[[David Crosby]]\n*[[Graham Nash]]\n*Roy Muniz\n*[[Jon Anderson]]\n*[[Pete Yorn]]\n*[[Jeff Young]]\n*[[Joe Bonamassa]]\n*[[Shaun Morgan]]\n*[[Josh Turner]]\n*[[Monte Montgomery]]\n*[[Mike Inez]]\n*[[Miguel Dakota]]\n*[[Viktor Tsoi]]\n*Rick Droit\n*[[Mason Ramsey]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last= |first= |title= Acoustic Guitars: The Illustrated Encyclopedia |location= New York |publisher= Chartwell Books |date = 2011 |pages =  |format= |isbn= 978-0-7858-3571-4}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alvarez Guitars}}\n*{{Official website|http://alvarezguitars.com}}\n\n{{Guitar brands}}\n\n[[Category:Guitar manufacturing companies of the United States|Alvarez Guitars]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in St. Louis]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alvarez_Guitars"}
{"title_page": "Alva Noto", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name            = Alva Noto\n| image           = RasterNoton-NotoLive.png\n| alt             =\n| caption         = Nicolai as ''Noto'', playing live at [[Mutek|MUTEK]] 2004\n| image_size      =\n| background      = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name      = Carsten Nicolai\n| alias           = Aleph-1, Alva Noto, Noto\n| birth_place     = [[Chemnitz|Karl-Marx-Stadt]], [[Saxony]]<br>[[GDR]]<ref name=\"carstennicolai\">[http://www.carstennicolai.de/?c=biography Carsten Nicolai biography]</ref>\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1965|9|18}}\n| death_date      =\n| instrument      = [[Synthesizer]]<br> [[electronic keyboard|keyboards]]<br>[[laptop]]<br>[[percussion]]\n| genre           = [[Electronic music]] \u00b7 [[Glitch (music)|glitch]] \u00b7 [[microsound]] \u00b7 [[minimal techno]] \u00b7 [[Ambient music|ambient]]\n| occupation      =\n| years_active    =\n| label           = NOTON [[Raster-Noton]]<br>[[Mille Plateaux (record label)|Mille Plateaux]]<br> Line\n| associated_acts = [[ANBB]]<br>[[Blixa Bargeld]]<br>[[Ryoji Ikeda]] <br>[[Ryuichi Sakamoto]]<br>Cyclo<br> Opto<br>Signal\n| website         = [http://www.alvanoto.com/ www.alvanoto.com]\n}}\n\n<!-- Do not use the \"dated prod\" template directly; the above line is generated by \"subst:prod|reason\" -->\n'''Carsten Nicolai''' (September 18, 1965), known as '''Alva Noto''', is a [[German people|German]] [[musician]]. He is a member of the music groups Diamond Version<ref>{{cite web |title=Alva Noto and Byetone collaborate as Diamond Version |url=https://www.thewire.co.uk/news/19171/alva-noto-and-byetone-collaborate-as-diamond-version |website=The Wire |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> with Olaf Bender (Byetone), Signal with [[Frank Bretschneider]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Panorama 5: Aural Optic - MUTEK 2012, Montreal |url=http://www.mutek.org/en/archives/artists/356-signal |website=MUTEK}}</ref> and Olaf Bender, Cyclo with [[Ryoji Ikeda]], [[ANBB]] with [[Blixa Bargeld]], ALPHABET with Anne-James Chaton<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carlos Hawthorn |title=Alva Noto and Anne-James Chaton reveal collaborative album as ALPHABET |url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/news/44625 |website=Resident Advisor |accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>, Opto with Thomas Knak, and Alva Noto + [[Ryuichi Sakamoto]] with whom he composed the score for the 2015 film ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]''.\n\n==Life and career==\nCarsten Nicolai was born in [[Karl-Marx-Stadt]] (now [[Chemnitz]]) of [[Saxony]], [[GDR]] in 1965. He studied architecture and landscape design before pursuing art. In 1994 he founded the label NOTON, following which a collaboration with RasterMusic began and by 1999 the two labels had merged into [[Raster-Noton]],\u00a0which operated until 2017. \nReturning to the labels origin in 2017, Nicolai runs [[NOTON]] separately <ref>{{cite web |title=Raster-Noton company to split in two |url=https://www.thewire.co.uk/news/46745/raster-noton-split-in-two |website=The Wire |publisher=The Wire |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>. \n\nIn 2009 Nicolai has written an opera, ''[[Sparkie Williams|Sparkie]]: Cage and Beyond'', in collaboration with [[Michael Nyman]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/tyne/7963007.stm | work=BBC News | title=Linguistic budgie inspires opera | date=2009-03-25 | accessdate=2010-04-23}}</ref>\n\nNicolai has performed and created installations in many of the world's most prestigious spaces including the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim]], [[New York City|New York]], the [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art|SF MoMA]], Modern Art Oxford, [[Nippon Telegraph and Telephone|NTT]] [[Tokyo]], [[Tate Modern]] and [[Venice Biennale]], [[Italy]]. As a member (and co-founder) of the Raster-Noton label he was responsible for the acclaimed CD series ''20 to 2000'' that went on to win the Golden Nica prize at [[Prix Ars Electronica]], 2000.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nCarsten Nicolai also works as a visual artist. In 2013, Nicolai participated as a visual artist in ''Biennale Documenta'', an official collateral show of the ''55th [[Venice Biennale]] of Art''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dearteassociazione.org/www.dearteassociazione.org/NOISE.html |title=''NOISE'': an exhibition organized by De Arte Association, curated by Marisa Vescovo |access-date=7 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613210509/http://www.dearteassociazione.org/www.dearteassociazione.org/NOISE.html |archive-date=13 June 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nNicolai started his professorship in art with focus on digital and time-based media with [[Dresden Academy of Fine Arts]] since 2015.\n\nNicolai scored the music for [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]] 's [[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]''. The score was nominated for a [[Golden Globe]], [[BAFTA]], [[Grammy]] and [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Revenant - Awards |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1663202/awards |website=IMDb |accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> In 2018 he created the sound design for I\u00f1\u00e1rritu\u2019s groundbreaking VR project \u201cCarne y Arena\u201d [[Flesh and Sand]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adriano D'Aloia |title=Virtually Present, Physically Invisible: Virtual reality immersion and emersion in Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu\u2019s Carne y Arena |url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2018/feature-articles/virtually-present-physically-invisible-virtual-reality-immersion-and-emersion-in-alejandro-gonzalez-inarritus-carne-y-arena/ |website=Senses of Cinema |accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Alva Noto solo studio albums===\n* ''[[Prototypes (Alva Noto album)|Prototypes]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2000 ([[Mille_Plateaux_(record_label)|Mille Plateaux]])\n*   module 4 \u2014 2001 (NOTON)\n* ''[[Transform (Alva Noto album)|Transform]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2001 (Mille Plateaux) & re-released on [[Raster-Noton]] in 2008 \n*   mort aoux vaches \u2014 2002 ([[Staalplaat]])\n* ''[[Xerrox Vol.1]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2007 (NOTON)\n* ''[[Unitxt]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2008 (NOTON)\n* ''[[Xerrox Vol.2]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2009 (NOTON)\n* ''[[Univrs]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2011 (NOTON)\n* ''[[Xerrox Vol.3]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2015 (NOTON)\n*   UNIEQAV \u2014 2018 (NOTON)\n*   UNIEQAV Remixes featuring reworks by ''[[Fatima Al Qadiri]]'', ''[[Ben Frost (musician)|Ben Frost]]'', JASSS, Florian Kupfer, Luis Da Silva \u2014 2020 (NOTON)\n\n===Alva Noto as Aleph-1 solo studio album===\n* ''[[Aleph-1 (Alva Noto album)|Aleph-1]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2007 (NOTON)\n\n=== Alva Noto extended plays ([[Extended play|EP]])===\n* ''[[Transrapid (Alva Noto EP)|Transrapid]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2005 [[Raster-Noton]]\n* ''[[Transvision (Alva Noto EP)|Transvision]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2005 [[Raster-Noton]]\n* ''[[Transspray]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2005 [[Raster-Noton]]\n\n===Alva Noto as noto solo studio albums===\n* spin \u2014 1996 (NOTON)\n* infinity \u2014 1997 (NOTON)\n* infinity (endless loop edition) \u2014 1997 (NOTON)\n* kerne \u2014 1998 (NOTON)\n* polyfoto \u2014 1998 (NOTON)\n* time..dot \u2014 1999 (NOTON)\n* empty garden, inside out '\u2014 1999 (NOTON)\n* telefunken \u2014 2000 (NOTON)\n* endless loop (e, f, g, h) \u2014 2002 (NOTON)\n* autorec \u2014 2002 (NOTON)\n* sonar endless edition \u2014 2003 (NOTON)\n\n===Alva Noto as anbb solo studio albums===\n* ret marut handshake \u2014 2010 (NOTON)\n* mimikry''\u2014 2010 (NOTON)\n\n===Compilation albums===\n*''[[for]]''\u2014 2006 (NOTON)\n*''[[for 2]]''\u2014 2010 (NOTON)\n\n===Soundtrack albums===\n* ''[[The Revenant (soundtrack)|The Revenant]]''&nbsp;\u2014 2015 [[Milan Records]]\n\n===Collaborations===\n;With [[Ryuichi Sakamoto]], as alva noto + ryuichi sakamoto\n* ''[[Vrioon]]''&nbsp;\u2014 December 2002 (Raster-Noton)\n* ''[[Insen]]''&nbsp;\u2014 March 2005 (Raster-Noton)\n* ''[