roprotective role of alpha-synuclein | journal = Experimental Neurology | volume = 200 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u20137 | date = July 2006 | pmid = 16780837 | doi = 10.1016/j.expneurol.2006.04.024 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Giorgi FS, Bandettini di Poggio A, Battaglia G, Pellegrini A, Murri L, Ruggieri S, Paparelli A, Fornai F | display-authors = 6 | title = A short overview on the role of alpha-synuclein and proteasome in experimental models of Parkinson's disease | journal = Journal of Neural Transmission. Supplementum | volume = 70 | issue = 70 | pages = 105\u20139 | year = 2006 | pmid = 17017516 | doi = 10.1007/978-3-211-45295-0_17 | series = <!-- --> | isbn = 978-3-211-28927-3 }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons-inline|Category:Alpha-synuclein|alpha synuclein}}\n* {{MeshName|alpha-Synuclein}}\n* {{UCSC gene info|SNCA}}\n\n{{PDB Gallery|geneid=6622}}\n{{Nerve tissue protein}}\n\n[[Category:Peripheral membrane proteins]]\n[[Category:Lewy body dementia]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha-synuclein"}
{"title_page": "Alpha-glucosidase inhibitor", "text_new": "'''Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors''' ('''AGIs''') are oral [[anti-diabetic drug]]s used for [[diabetes mellitus type 2]] that work by preventing the digestion of carbohydrates (such as [[starch]] and [[sucrose|table sugar]]). Carbohydrates are normally converted into simple sugars ([[monosaccharide]]s) by alpha-glucosidase enzymes present on cells lining the intestine, enabling monosaccharides to be absorbed through the intestine.  Hence, alpha-glucosidase inhibitors reduce the impact of dietary carbohydrates on [[blood sugar]].\n\n==Examples and differences==\nExamples of alpha-glucosidase inhibitors include:\n* [[Acarbose]]- Precose or Glucobay\n* [[Miglitol]] \u2013 Glyset\n* [[Voglibose]]\n\nEven though the drugs have a similar mechanism of action, there are subtle differences between acarbose and miglitol.  Acarbose is an [[oligosaccharide]], whereas miglitol resembles a [[monosaccharide]].  Miglitol is fairly well absorbed by the body, as opposed to acarbose.  Moreover, acarbose inhibits pancreatic alpha-amylase in addition to alpha-glucosidase.\n\n==Natural alpha glucosidase inhibitors==\nThere are a large number of natural products with alpha-glucosidase inhibitor action.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2174/157339910791658826 |title=Antidiabetic Medicinal Plants as a Source of Alpha Glucosidase Inhibitors |year=2010 |last1=Benalla |first1=Wafaa |last2=Bellahcen |first2=Said |last3=Bnouham |first3=Mohamed |journal=Current Diabetes Reviews |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=247\u201354 |pmid=20522017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.4268/cjcmm20101229 |script-title=zh:\u836f\u7528\u690d\u7269\u6765\u6e90\u7684\u03b1-\u8461\u8404\u7cd6\u82f7\u9176\u6291\u5236\u5242\u7814\u7a76\u8fdb\u5c55 |trans-title=Development of \u03b1-glucosidase inhibitor from medicinal herbs |language=Chinese |year=2010 |first1=Fang |last1=Ji |first2=Guochun |last2=Xiao |first3=Li |last3=Dong |first4=Zijiao |last4=Ma |first5=Jingman |last5=Ni |journal=China Journal of Chinese Materia Medica |volume=35 |issue=12 |pmid=20815224 |pages=1633\u201340}}</ref>\n\nFor example, research has shown the culinary mushroom [[Maitake]] (''Grifola frondosa'') has a [[blood sugar|hypoglycemic]] effect.<ref name=\"pmid11903406\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1046/j.1464-5491.2001.00532-5.x |title=A possible hypoglycaemic effect of maitake mushroom on Type 2 diabetic patients |year=2001 |last1=Konno |first1=S. |last2=Tortorelis |first2=D. G. |last3=Fullerton |first3=S. A. |last4=Samadi |first4=A. A. |last5=Hettiarachchi |first5=J. |last6=Tazaki |first6=H. |journal=Diabetic Medicine |volume=18 |issue=12 |pages=1010 |pmid=11903406}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid17430642\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1211/jpp.59.4.0013 |title=Anti-diabetic effect of an \u03b1-glucan from fruit body of maitake (''Grifola frondosa'') on KK-Ay mice |year=2007 |last1=Hong |first1=Lei |last2=Xun |first2=Ma |last3=Wutong |first3=Wu |journal=Journal of Pharmacy and Pharmacology |volume=59 |issue=4 |pages=575\u201382 |pmid=17430642}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid7820117\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1248/bpb.17.1106 |title=Anti-diabetic Activity Present in the Fruit Body of Grifola frondosa (Maitake). I |year=1994 |last1=Kubo |first1=Keiko |last2=Aoki |first2=Hisao |last3=Nanba |first3=Hiroaki |journal=Biological & Pharmaceutical Bulletin |volume=17 |issue=8 |pages=1106\u201310 |pmid=7820117}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid18457360\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1142/S0192415X0800576X |title=Submerged Culture Mycelium and Broth of ''Grifola frondosa'' Improve Glycemic Responses in Diabetic Rats |year=2008 |last1=Lo |first1=Hui-Chen |last2=Hsu |first2=Tai-Hao |last3=Chen |first3=Ching-Yi |journal=The American Journal of Chinese Medicine |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=265\u201385 |pmid=18457360}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid11874441\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1046/j.1463-1326.2002.00180.x |title=Effects of a water-soluble extract of maitake mushroom on circulating glucose/insulin concentrations in KK mice |year=2002 |last1=Manohar |first1=V. |last2=Talpur |first2=N. A. |last3=Echard |first3=B. W. |last4=Lieberman |first4=S. |last5=Preuss |first5=H. G. |journal=Diabetes, Obesity and Metabolism |volume=4 |pages=43\u20138 |pmid=11874441 |issue=1}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid11349892\">{{cite journal |doi=10.3177/jnsv.47.57 |title=Maitake (Grifola frondosa) Improve Glucose Tolerance of Experimental Diabetic Rats |year=2001 |last1=Horio |first1=Hiroyuki |last2=Ohtsuru |first2=Masaru |journal=Journal of Nutritional Science and Vitaminology |volume=47 |pages=57\u201363 |pmid=11349892 |issue=1}}</ref>  The reason Maitake lowers blood sugar is because the mushroom naturally contains an alpha glucosidase inhibitor.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1271/bbb.66.1576 |title=\u03b1-Glucosidase Inhibitor from the Seeds of Balsam Pear (''Momordica charantia'') and the Fruit Bodies of ''Grifola frondosa'' |year=2002 |last1=Matsuura |first1=Hideyuki |last2=Asakawa |first2=Chikako |last3=Kurimoto |first3=Masanori |last4=Mizutani |first4=Junya |journal=Bioscience, Biotechnology, and Biochemistry |volume=66 |issue=7 |pages=1576\u20138 |pmid=12224646}}</ref>\nAnother plant attracting a lot of attention is  ''[[Salacia oblonga]]''. /{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\n==Clinical use==\n[[Alpha-glucosidase]] inhibitors are used to establish greater [[Diabetes management#Glycemic control|glycemic control]] over [[hyperglycemia]] in [[diabetes mellitus type 2]], particularly with regard to [[postprandial]] hyperglycemia.  They may be used as monotherapy in conjunction with an appropriate [[diabetic diet]] and exercise, or they may be used in conjunction with other anti-diabetic drugs.\n\nIn patients with [[diabetes mellitus type 1]], Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors use has not been officially approved by the [[Food and Drug Administration]] but some data exists on the effectiveness in this population, showing potential benefits weighted against an increased risk of hypoglycemia.<ref>Alternative Agents in Type 1 Diabetes in Addition to Insulin Therapy: Metformin, Alpha-Glucosidase Inhibitors, Pioglitazone, GLP-1 Agonists, DPP-IV Inhibitors, and SGLT-2 Inhibitors. Michelle DeGeeter, PharmD, CDE, Bobbie Williamson, PharmD, BCACP, CDE. Journal of Pharmacy Practice Vol 29, Issue 2, pp. 144 - 159. First Published October 13, 2014 https://doi.org/10.1177/0897190014549837</ref>\n\n==Mechanism of action==\nAlpha-glucosidase inhibitors are [[saccharide]]s that act as [[competitive inhibitor]]s of enzymes needed to digest [[carbohydrate]]s: specifically [[alpha-glucosidase]] enzymes in the brush border of the small intestines. The membrane-bound intestinal [[alpha-glucosidase]]s hydrolyze [[oligosaccharide]]s, [[trisaccharide]]s, and [[disaccharide]]s to [[glucose]] and other monosaccharides in the small intestine.\n\nAcarbose also blocks pancreatic alpha-amylase in addition to inhibiting membrane-bound alpha-glucosidases.  [[Pancreatic]] [[alpha-amylase]] hydrolyzes complex starches to [[oligosaccharides]] in the lumen of the small intestine.\n\nInhibition of these enzyme systems reduces the rate of digestion of carbohydrates. Less glucose is absorbed because the carbohydrates are not broken down into glucose molecules. In [[diabetic]] patients, the short-term effect of these drugs therapies is to decrease current blood glucose levels: the long-term effect is a small reduction in [[glycosylated hemoglobin|hemoglobin <sub>A1c</sub>]] level.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Samantha J. |last1=Venable |first2=Diane S. |last2=Aschenbrenner |title=Drug Therapy In Nursing |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location=Hagerstown, MD |year=2006 |pages= |isbn=0-7817-4839-9 |oclc= |doi= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/drugtherapyinnur00asch }}{{page needed|date=February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Dosing==\nSince alpha-glucosidase inhibitors are competitive inhibitors of digestive enzymes, they must be taken at the start of main meals to have maximal effect.  Their effects on blood sugar levels following meals will depend on the amount of complex carbohydrates in the meal.\n\n==Side effects and precautions==\nSince alpha-glucosidase inhibitors prevent the degradation of complex carbohydrates into glucose, the carbohydrates will remain in the intestine.  In the [[Colon (anatomy)|colon]], bacteria will digest the complex carbohydrates, thereby causing gastrointestinal side effects such as [[flatulence]] and [[diarrhea]].  Since these effects are dose-related, it is generally advised to start with a low dose and gradually increase the dose to the desired amount.\n[[Pneumatosis cystoides intestinalis]] is another reported side effect.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}\nIf a patient using an alpha-glucosidase inhibitor suffers from an episode of [[hypoglycemia]], the patient should eat something containing monosaccharides, such as glucose tablets.  Since the drug will prevent the digestion of polysaccharides (or non-monosaccharides), non-monosaccharide foods may not effectively reverse a hypoglycemic episode in a patient taking an alpha-glucosidase inhibitor.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alpha-glucosidase]]\n* [[Alpha amylase inhibitor]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Oral hypoglycemics}}\n{{Enzyme inhibition}}\n\n[[Category:Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors]]\n", "text_old": "'''Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors''' ('''AGIs''') are oral [[anti-diabetic drug]]s used for [[diabetes mellitus type 2]] that work by preventing the digestion of carbohydrates (such as [[starch]] and [[sucrose|table sugar]]). Carbohydrates are normally converted into simple sugars ([[monosaccharide]]s) by alpha-glucosidase enzymes present on cells lining the intestine, enabling monosaccharides to be absorbed through the intestine.  Hence, alpha-glucosidase inhibitors reduce the impact of dietary carbohydrates on [[blood sugar]].\n\n==Examples and differences==\nExamples of alpha-glucosidase inhibitors include:\n* [[Acarbose]]- Precose or Glucobay\n* [[Miglitol]] \u2013 Glyset\n* [[Voglibose]]\n\nEven though the drugs have a similar mechanism of action, there are subtle differences between acarbose and miglitol.  Acarbose is an [[oligosaccharide]], whereas miglitol resembles a [[monosaccharide]].  Miglitol is fairly well absorbed by the body, as opposed to acarbose.  Moreover, acarbose inhibits pancreatic alpha-amylase in addition to alpha-glucosidase.\n\n==Natural alpha glucosidase inhibitors==\nThere are a large number of natural products with alpha-glucosidase inhibitor action.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2174/157339910791658826 |title=Antidiabetic Medicinal Plants as a Source of Alpha Glucosidase Inhibitors |year=2010 |last1=Benalla |first1=Wafaa |last2=Bellahcen |first2=Said |last3=Bnouham |first3=Mohamed |journal=Current Diabetes Reviews |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=247\u201354 |pmid=20522017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.4268/cjcmm20101229 |script-title=zh:\u836f\u7528\u690d\u7269\u6765\u6e90\u7684\u03b1-\u8461\u8404\u7cd6\u82f7\u9176\u6291\u5236\u5242\u7814\u7a76\u8fdb\u5c55 |trans-title=Development of \u03b1-glucosidase inhibitor from medicinal herbs |language=Chinese |year=2010 |first1=Fang |last1=Ji |first2=Guochun |last2=Xiao |first3=Li |last3=Dong |first4=Zijiao |last4=Ma |first5=Jingman |last5=Ni |journal=China Journal of Chinese Materia Medica |volume=35 |issue=12 |pmid=20815224 |pages=1633\u201340}}</ref>\n\nFor example, research has shown the culinary mushroom [[Maitake]] (''Grifola frondosa'') has a [[blood sugar|hypoglycemic]] effect.<ref name=\"pmid11903406\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1046/j.1464-5491.2001.00532-5.x |title=A possible hypoglycaemic effect of maitake mushroom on Type 2 diabetic patients |year=2001 |last1=Konno |first1=S. |last2=Tortorelis |first2=D. G. |last3=Fullerton |first3=S. A. |last4=Samadi |first4=A. A. |last5=Hettiarachchi |first5=J. |last6=Tazaki |first6=H. |journal=Diabetic Medicine |volume=18 |issue=12 |pages=1010 |pmid=11903406}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid17430