}}\nIf a patient using an alpha-glucosidase inhibitor suffers from an episode of [[hypoglycemia]], the patient should eat something containing monosaccharides, such as glucose tablets.  Since the drug will prevent the digestion of polysaccharides (or non-monosaccharides), non-monosaccharide foods may not effectively reverse a hypoglycemic episode in a patient taking an alpha-glucosidase inhibitor.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alpha-glucosidase]]\n* [[Alpha amylase inhibitor]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Oral hypoglycemics}}\n{{Enzyme inhibition}}\n\n[[Category:Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha-glucosidase_inhibitor"}
{"title_page": "Alnilam", "text_new": "{{short description|Blue supergiant star in the constellation Orion}}\n{{Starbox begin}}\n{{Starbox image\n | image=\n{{Location mark\n|image=Orion constellation map.svg|alt=|float=center|width=260\n|label=|position=right\n|mark=Red circle.svg|mark_width=12|mark_link=Alnilam\n|x=579|y=548\n}}\n|caption=Location of Alnilam (circled)\n}}\n{{Starbox observe\n | epoch=J2000\n | ra={{RA|05|36|12.8}}<ref name=hipparcos>{{cite journal|title=Validation of the new Hipparcos reduction|first=F.|last=van Leeuwen|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=474 |issue=2 |date=November 2007|pages=653\u2013664|bibcode=2007A&A...474..653V|arxiv = 0708.1752 |doi = 10.1051/0004-6361:20078357 }}</ref>\n | dec={{DEC|\u221201|12|06.9}}<ref name=hipparcos/>\n | appmag_v=1.69<ref name=ducati>{{cite journal|title=VizieR Online Data Catalog: Catalogue of Stellar Photometry in Johnson's 11-color system|journal=CDS/ADC Collection of Electronic Catalogues |volume=2237 |last=Ducati |first=J. R.|date=2002|bibcode=2002yCat.2237....0D}}</ref> {{nowrap|(1.64 \u2013 1.74<ref name=ruban/>)}}\n | constell=[[Orion (constellation)|Orion]]\n}}\n{{Starbox character\n | class=B0&nbsp;Ia<ref name=mkk/>\n | b-v=\u22120.18<ref name=ducati/>\n | u-b=\u22121.03<ref name=ducati/>\n | variable=[[Alpha cygni variable|\u03b1 Cygni]]<ref name=ruban>{{cite journal|title=Spectrophotometric observations of variable stars|first=E. V. |last=Ruban |first2=G. A. |last2=Alekseeva |first3=A. A. |last3=Arkharov |first4=E. I. |last4=Hagen-Thorn |first5=V. D. |last5=Galkin |first6=I. N. |last6=Nikanorova |first7=V. V. |last7=Novikov |first8=V. P. |last8=Pakhomov |first9=T. Yu. |last9=Puzakova|journal=Astronomy Letters|date=September 2006 |volume=32 |issue=9 |pages=604\u2013607|doi=10.1134/S1063773706090052|bibcode = 2006AstL...32..604R|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/e20a5ea57e3d4f30c9789e91b2c846770ab09ad7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Starbox astrometry\n | radial_v=25.9<ref>{{cite journal|title=Pulkovo Compilation of Radial Velocities for 35 495 Hipparcos stars in a common system|first=G. A. |last=Gontcharov|journal=Astronomy Letters|date=November 2006 |volume=32 |issue=11 |pages=759\u2013771|bibcode=2006AstL...32..759G|doi = 10.1134/S1063773706110065 |arxiv = 1606.08053 }}</ref>\n | prop_mo_ra=1.49<ref name=hipparcos/>\n | prop_mo_dec=\u22121.06<ref name=hipparcos/>\n | parallax=1.65\n | p_error=0.45\n | parallax_footnote=<ref name=hipparcos/>\n | absmag_v=\u22126.89<ref name=\"Searle 2008\"/>\n }}\n{{Starbox detail\n | mass=40<ref name=\"Searle 2008\"/>\n | radius=32.4<ref name=\"Searle 2008\"/>\n | luminosity=537,000<ref name=\"Searle 2008\"/>\n | temperature=27,500\u00b1100<ref name=\"Searle 2008\"/>\n | gravity=3.0<ref name=puebla/>\n | metal=\n | rotational_velocity=40\u201370<ref name=puebla/>\n | age_myr=5.7<ref name=\"Voss 2010\"/>\n}}\n{{Starbox catalog\n | names=Alnilam, [[Bayer designation|\u03b5]]&nbsp;Ori, [[Flamsteed designation|46]]&nbsp;Orionis, [[Gould designation|112&nbsp;G]]&nbsp;Orionis, [[Harvard Revised catalogue|HR]]&nbsp;1903, [[Bonner Durchmusterung|BD]]&nbsp;-01\u00b0969, [[Henry Draper catalogue|HD]]&nbsp;37128, [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory Star Catalog|SAO]]&nbsp;132346, [[FK5]]&nbsp;210, [[Hipparcos catalogue|HIP]]&nbsp;26311, TD1&nbsp;4963, [[Three Stars (Chinese constellation)|\u53c2\u5bbf\u4e8c]]\n}}\n{{Starbox reference\n | Simbad=HD+37128\n}}\n{{Starbox end}}\n'''Alnilam''' {{IPAc-en|\u00e6|l|'|n|ai|l|\u00e6|m}}<!--not the expected stress etymologically, but seems standard-->,<ref name=Kunitzsch>{{cite book\n  |last=Kunitzsch |first=Paul\n  |last2=Smart |first2=Tim\n  |date = 2006  |edition = 2nd rev.\n  |title = A Dictionary of Modern star Names: A Short Guide to 254 Star Names and Their Derivations\n  |publisher = Sky Pub |location = Cambridge, Massachusetts\n  |isbn = 978-1-931559-44-7\n}}</ref> designation '''\u03b5 Orionis''', ([[Latinisation of names|Latinized]] to '''Epsilon Orionis''', abbreviated '''Epsilon Ori''', '''\u03b5 Ori''') and '''46&nbsp;Orionis''' ('''46 Ori'''), is a large [[blue supergiant star]] some 2,000 [[light-year]]s distant in the [[constellation]] of [[Orion (constellation)|Orion]]. It is estimated to be 275,000 to 832,000 times as [[Solar luminosity|luminous as the Sun]], and 30\u201364.5 times [[Solar mass|as massive]].\n\n==Observation==\n[[Image:Orion Belt.jpg|thumb|left|Alnilam is the middle and brightest of the three stars of Orion's Belt]]\nIt is the [[List of brightest stars|29th-brightest star]] in the sky (the 4th-brightest in Orion) and is a [[blue supergiant]]. Together with [[Mintaka]] and [[Alnitak]], the three stars make up [[Orion's Belt|Orion's belt]], known by many names across many ancient cultures. Alnilam is the middle star. It is slightly variable, from magnitude 1.64 to 1.74.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sai.msu.su/gcvs/cgi-bin/search.cgi?search=eps+Ori|title=GCVS Query forms|website=www.sai.msu.su|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> Since 1943, the [[stellar spectrum|spectrum]] of this [[star]] has served as one of the stable anchor points by which other stars are classified.<ref name=mkk>{{cite journal |title=An Atlas of Stellar Spectra |doi=10.1038/152147a0 |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/ucl-observatory/sites/ucl-observatory/files/mkkbook.pdf|journal=Astrophysical Monographs |volume=152 |issue=3849 |pages=147 |date=1943 |last=Morgan |first=W. W. |last2=Keenan |first2=Philip C. |last3=Kellman |first3=Edith |bibcode=1943Natur.152..147. }}</ref> It is also one of the [[Navigational stars|58&nbsp;stars]] used in [[celestial navigation]]. It is at its highest point in the sky around midnight on December 15. \n\n==Physical characteristics==\nEstimates of Alnilam's properties vary. Crowther and colleagues, using stellar wind and atmospheric modelling in 2006, came up with a luminosity 275,000 times that of the Sun ({{solar luminosity|link=y}}), and effective temperature of 27,000 K and a radius 24 times that of the Sun ({{solar radius|link=y}}).<ref name=\"crowther\">{{cite journal|last=Crowther|first=P. A.|last2=Lennon|first2=D. J.|last3=Walborn|first3=N. R.|date=January 2006|title=Physical parameters and wind properties of galactic early B supergiants|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=446|issue=1|pages=279\u2013293|arxiv=astro-ph/0509436|bibcode=2006A&A...446..279C|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20053685}}</ref> Searle and colleagues, using CMFGEN code to analyse the spectrum in 2008, calculated a luminosity of {{solar luminosity| 537,000}}, an effective temperature of 27,500 \u00b1 100 K and a radius of {{solar radius|32.4 \u00b1 0.75}}.<ref name=\"Searle 2008\">{{cite journal|author=Searle, S. C.|author2=Prinja, R. K.|author3=Massa, D.|author4=Ryans, R.|date=2008|title=Quantitative studies of the optical and UV spectra of Galactic early B supergiants. I. Fundamental parameters|journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics|volume=481|issue=3|pages=777\u201397|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20077125 |bibcode=2008A&A...481..777S |arxiv = 0801.4289 }}</ref> Analysis of the spectra and age of the members of the Orion OB1 association yields a mass 34.6 times that of the Sun ({{solar mass|40.8}} on the [[main sequence]]) and an age of 5.7 million years.<ref name=\"Voss 2010\">{{cite journal|author= Voss, R.|author2= Diehl, R.|author3= Vink, J. S.|author4= Hartmann, D. H.|date=2010|title=Probing the evolving massive star population in Orion with kinematic and radioactive tracers|journal= Astronomy and Astrophysics|volume=520|pages=10|id=A51 | doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201014408|bibcode=2010A&A...520A..51V|arxiv = 1005.3827 }}</ref>\n\nA more recent detailed analysis of Alnilam across multiple wavelength bands produced very high luminosity, radius, and mass estimates, assuming the distance of 606 [[parsec]]s suggested by the Hipparcos new reduction.<ref name=hipparcos/> Adopting the larger parallax from the original Hipparcos reduction gives a distance of 412 parsecs<ref name=perryman>{{cite journal|bibcode=1997A&A...323L..49P|title=The HIPPARCOS Catalogue|journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics |volume=323|pages=L49|last1=Perryman|first1=M. A. C.|last2=Lindegren|first2=L.|last3=Kovalevsky|first3=J.|last4=Hoeg|first4=E.|last5=Bastian|first5=U.|last6=Bernacca|first6=P. L.|last7=Cr\u00e9z\u00e9|first7=M.|last8=Donati|first8=F.|last9=Grenon|first9=M.|last10=Grewing|first10=M.|last11=Van Leeuwen|first11=F.|last12=Van Der Marel|first12=H.|last13=Mignard|first13=F.|last14=Murray|first14=C. A.|last15=Le Poole|first15=R. S.|last16=Schrijver|first16=H.|last17=Turon|first17=C.|last18=Arenou|first18=F.|last19=Froeschl\u00e9|first19=M.|last20=Petersen|first20=C. S.|date=1997}}</ref> and physical parameters more consistent with earlier publications. The luminosity of {{solar luminosity|832,000}} at 606 parsecs is the highest ever derived for this star.<ref name=\"puebla\">{{cite journal|author=Puebla, R.E. |author2=Hillier, D.J. |author3=Zsarg\u00f3, J. |author4=Cohen, D.H. |author5=Leutenegger, M.A.|date=2015|title=X-ray, UV and optical analysis of supergiants: \u03f5 Ori|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=456|issue=3|pages=2907\u20132936|doi=10.1093/mnras/stv2783 |bibcode=2016MNRAS.456.2907P|arxiv = 1511.09365 }}</ref>\n\nAlnilam's relatively simple spectrum has made it useful for studying the [[interstellar medium]]. Within the next million years, this star may turn into a [[red supergiant]] and explode as a [[supernova]]. It is surrounded by a [[molecular cloud]], [[NGC 1990]], which it illuminates to make a [[reflection nebula]]. Its [[stellar wind]]s may reach up to 2000 [[velocity|km/s]], causing it to lose [[mass]] about 20 million times more rapidly than the Sun.<ref name=\"crowther\" />\n\n== Nomenclature and history ==\n''\u03b5 Orionis'' is the star's [[Bayer designation]] and ''46&nbsp;Orionis'' its [[Flamsteed designation]].\n\nThe traditional name ''Alnilam'' derives from the [[Arabic]] \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0638\u0627\u0645 ''al-ni\u1e93\u0101m'' 'arrangement/string (of pearls)'. Related spellings are ''Alnihan'' and ''Alnitam'':<ref name=allen>{{Cite book |first=Richard Hinckley |last=Allen |title=Star-names and their meanings |date=1936 |pages=314\u2013315 }}</ref> all three variants are evidently mistakes in transliteration or copy errors, the first perhaps due to confusion with \u0627\u0644\u0646\u064a\u0644\u0645 ''al-nilam'' '[[sapphire]]'.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The name of epsilon Orionis|last=Knobel |first=E. B.|journal=The Observatory |volume=32 |page=357|date=September 1909|bibcode=1909Obs....32..357K}}</ref> In 2016, the [[International Astronomical Union]] organized a [[IAU Working Group on Star Names|Working Group on Star Names]] (WGSN)<ref name=\"WGSN\">{{cite web | url=https://www.iau.org/science/scientific_bodies/working_groups/280/ | title=IAU Working Group on Star Names (WGSN)|accessdate=22 May 2016}}</ref> to catalog and standardize proper names for stars. The WGSN's first bulletin of July 2016<ref name=\"WGSN1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/WGSN_bulletin1.pdf | title=Bulletin of the IAU Working Group on Star Names, No. 1 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> included a table of the first two batches of names approved by the WGSN; which included ''Alnilam'' for this star. It is now so entered in the IAU Catalog of Star Names.<ref name=\"IAU-CSN\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/IAU-CSN.txt | title=IAU Catalog of Star Names |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Orion's Belt===\n{{Main article|Orion's Belt}}\nThe three belt stars were collectively known by many names in many cultures. Arabic terms include ''Al Nij\u0101d'' 'the Belt', ''Al Nasak'' 'the Line', ''Al Alk\u0101t'' 'the Golden Grains or Nuts', and, in modern Arabic, ''Al M\u012bz\u0101n al H\u2022akk'' 'the Accurate Scale Beam'. In [[Chinese mythology]], they were also known as The Weighing Beam.<ref name=allen/> \n\nIn [[Chinese astronomy|Chinese]], {{lang|zh|\u53c3\u5bbf}} ({{lang|zh-Latn|Sh\u0113n S\u00f9}}), meaning ''[[Three Stars (Chinese constellation)|Three Stars]] (asterism)'', refers to an asterism consisting of Alnilam, [[Alnitak]], and [[Mintaka]] (Orion's Belt), with [[Betelgeuse]], [[Bellatrix]], [[Saiph]], and [[Rigel]] later added.<ref>{{in lang|zh}} ''\u4e2d\u570b\u661f\u5ea7\u795e\u8a71'', written by \u9673\u4e45\u91d1. Published by \u53f0\u7063\u66f8\u623f\u51fa\u7248\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8, 2005, {{ISBN|978-986-7332-25-7}}.</ref> Consequently, the [[Chinese star names|Chinese name]] for Alnilam is {{lang|zh|\u53c3\u5bbf\u4e8c}} ({{lang|zh-Latn|Sh\u0113n S\u00f9 \u00e8r}}, {{lang-en|the Second Star of Three Stars}}).<ref>{{in lang|zh}}  [http://aeea.nmns.edu.tw/2006/0605/ap060525.html AEEA (Activities of Exhibition and Education in Astronomy) \u5929\u6587\u6559\u80b2\u8cc7\u8a0a\u7db2 2006 \u5e74 5 \u6708 25 \u65e5]</ref> It is one of the western mansions of the [[White Tiger (Chinese astronomy)|White Tiger]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Stars and planetary systems in fiction#Alnilam (Epsilon Orionis)|Alnilam in fiction]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{APOD |date=29 September 2009 |title=Image of Alnilam}}\n\n{{Stars of Orion}}\n\n{{Sky|05|36|12.8|-|01|12|06.9|800}}\n\n[[Category:Bayer objects|Orionis, Epsilon]]\n[[Category:B-type supergiants]]\n[[Category:Flamsteed objects|Orionis, 46]]\n[[Category:Orion (constellation)]]\n[[Category:Stars with proper names]]\n[[Category:Alpha Cygni variables]]\n[[Category:Durchmusterung objects|BD-01 0969]]\n[[Category:Henry Draper Catalogue objects|037128]]\n[[Category:Hipparcos objects|026311]]\n[[Category:HR objects|1903]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Blue supergiant star in the constellation Orion}}\n{{Starbox begin}}\n{{Starbox image\n | image=\n{{Location mark\n|image=Orion constellation map.svg|alt=|float=center|width=260\n|label=|position=right\n|mark=Red circle.svg|mark_width=12|mark_link=Alnilam\n|x=579|y=548\n}}\n|caption=Location of Alnilam (circled)\n}}\n{{Starbox observe\n | epoch=J2000\n | ra={{RA|05|36|12.8}}<ref name=hipparcos>{{cite journal|title=Validation of the new Hipparcos reduction|first=F.|last=van Leeuwen|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=474 |issue=2 |date=November 2007|pages=653\u2013664|bibcode=2007A&A...474..653V|arxiv = 0708.1752 |doi = 10.1051/0004-6361:20078357 }}</ref>\n | dec={{DEC|\u221201|12|06.9}}<ref name=hipparcos/>\n | appmag_v=1.69<ref name=ducati>{{cite journal|title=VizieR Online Data Catalog: Catalogue of Stellar Photometry in Johnson's 11-color system|journal=CDS/ADC Collection of Electronic Catalogues |volume=2237 |last=Ducati |first=J. R.|date=2002|bibcode=2002yCat.2237....0D}}</ref> {{nowrap|(1.64 \u2013 1.74<ref name=ruban/>)}}\n | constell=[[Orion (constellation)|Orion]]\n}}\n{{Starbox character\n | class=B0&nbsp;Ia<ref name=mkk/>\n | b-v=\u22120.18<ref name=ducati/>\n | u-b=\u22121.03<ref name=ducati/>\n | variable=[[Alpha cygni variable|\u03b1 Cygni]]<ref name=ruban>{{cite journal|title=Spectrophotometric observations of variable stars|first=E. V. |last=Ruban |first2=G. A. |last2=Alekseeva |first3=A. A. |last3=Arkharov |first4=E. I. |last4=Hagen-Thorn |first5=V. D. |last5=Galkin |first6=I. N. |last6=Nikanorova |first7=V. V. |last7=Novikov |first8=V. P. |last8=Pakhomov |first9=T. Yu. |last9=Puzakova|journal=Astronomy Letters|date=September 2006 |volume=32 |issue=9 |pages=604\u2013607|doi=10.1134/S1063773706090052|bibcode = 2006AstL...32..604R|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/e20a5ea57e3d4f30c9789e91b2c846770ab09ad7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Starbox astrometry\n | radial_v=25.9<ref>{{cite journal|title=Pulkovo Compilation of Radial Velocities for 35 495 Hipparcos stars in a common system|first=G. A. |last=Gontcharov|journal=Astronomy Letters|date=November 2006 |volume=32 |issue=11 |pages=759\u2013771|bibcode=2006AstL...32..759G|doi = 10.1134/S1063773706110065 |arxiv = 1606.08053 }}</ref>\n | prop_mo_ra=1.49<ref name=hipparcos/>\n | prop_mo_dec=\u22121.06<ref name=hipparcos/>\n | parallax=1.65\n | p_error=0.45\n | parallax_footnote=<ref name=hipparcos/>\n | absmag_v=\u22126.89<ref name=\"Searle 2008\"/>\n }}\n{{Starbox detail\n | mass=40<ref name=\"Searle 2008\"/>\n | radius=32.4<ref name=\"Searle 2008\"/>\n | luminosity=537,000<ref name=\"Searle 2008\"/>\n | temperature=27,500\u00b1100<ref name=\"Searle 2008\"/>\n | gravity=3.0<ref name=puebla/>\n | metal=\n | rotational_velocity=40\u201370<ref name=puebla/>\n | age_myr=5.7<ref name=\"Voss 2010\"/>\n}}\n{{Starbox catalog\n | names=Alnilam, [[Bayer designation|\u03b5]]&nbsp;Ori, [[Flamsteed designation|46]]&nbsp;Orionis, [[Gould designation|112&nbsp;G]]&nbsp;Orionis, [[Harvard Revised catalogue|HR]]&nbsp;1903, [[Bonner Durchmusterung|BD]]&nbsp;-01\u00b0969, [[Henry Draper catalogue|HD]]&nbsp;37128, [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory Star Catalog|SAO]]&nbsp;132346, [[FK5]]&nbsp;210, [[Hipparcos catalogue|HIP]]&nbsp;26311, TD1&nbsp;4963, [[Three Stars (Chinese constellation)|\u53c2\u5bbf\u4e8c]]\n}}\n{{Starbox reference\n | Simbad=HD+37128\n}}\n{{Starbox end}}\n'''Alnilam''' {{IPAc-en|\u00e6|l|'|n|ai|l|\u00e6|m}}<!--not the expected stress etymologically, but seems standard-->,<ref name=Kunitzsch>{{cite book\n  |last=Kunitzsch |first=Paul\n  |last2=Smart |first2=Tim\n  |date = 2006  |edition = 2nd rev.\n  |title = A Dictionary of Modern star Names: A Short Guide to 254 Star Names and Their Derivations\n  |publisher = Sky Pub |location = Cambridge, Massachusetts\n  |isbn = 978-1-931559-44-7\n}}</ref> designation '''\u03b5 Orionis''', ([[Latinisation of names|Latinized]] to '''Epsilon Orionis''', abbreviated '''Epsilon Ori''', '''\u03b5 Ori''') and '''46&nbsp;Orionis''' ('''46 Ori'''), is a large [[blue supergiant star]] some 2,000 [[light-year]]s distant in the [[constellation]] of [[Orion (constellation)|Orion]]. It is estimated to be 275,000 to 832,000 times as [[Solar luminosity|luminous as the Sun]], and 30\u201364.5 times [[Solar mass|as massive]].\n\n==Observation==\n[[Image:Orion Belt.jpg|thumb|left|Alnilam is the middle and brightest of the three stars of Orion's Belt]]\nIt is the [[List of brightest stars|29th-brightest star]] in the sky (the 4th-brightest in Orion) and is a [[blue supergiant]]. Together with [[Mintaka]] and [[Alnitak]], the three stars make up [[Orion's Belt|Orion's belt]], known by many names across many ancient cultures. Alnilam is the middle star. It is slightly variable, from magnitude 1.64 to 1.74<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sai.msu.su/gcvs/cgi-bin/search.cgi?search=eps+Ori|title=GCVS Query forms|website=www.sai.msu.su|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref>. Since 1943, the [[stellar spectrum|spectrum]] of this [[star]] has served as one of the stable anchor points by which other stars are classified.<ref name=mkk>{{cite journal |title=An Atlas of Stellar Spectra |doi=10.1038/152147a0 |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/ucl-observatory/sites/ucl-observatory/files/mkkbook.pdf|journal=Astrophysical Monographs |volume=152 |issue=3849 |pages=147 |date=1943 |last=Morgan |first=W. W. |last2=Keenan |first2=Philip C. |last3=Kellman |first3=Edith |bibcode=1943Natur.152..147. }}</ref> It is also one of the [[Navigational stars|58&nbsp;stars]] used in [[celestial navigation]]. It is at its highest point in the sky around midnight on December 15. \n\n==Physical characteristics==\nEstimates of Alnilam's properties vary. Crowther and colleagues, using stellar wind and atmospheric modelling in 2006, came up with a luminosity 275,000 times that of the Sun ({{solar luminosity|link=y}}), and effective temperature of 27,000 K and a radius 24 times that of the Sun ({{solar radius|link=y}}).<ref name=\"crowther\">{{cite journal|last=Crowther|first=P. A.|last2=Lennon|first2=D. J.|last3=Walborn|first3=N. R.|date=January 2006|title=Physical parameters and wind properties of galactic early B supergiants|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=446|issue=1|pages=279\u2013293|arxiv=astro-ph/0509436|bibcode=2006A&A...446..279C|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20053685}}</ref> Searle and colleagues, using CMFGEN code to analyse the spectrum in 2008, calculated a luminosity of {{solar luminosity| 537,000}}, an effective temperature of 27,500 \u00b1 100 K and a radius of {{solar radius|32.4 \u00b1 0.75}}.<ref name=\"Searle 2008\">{{cite journal|author=Searle, S. C.|author2=Prinja, R. K.|author3=Massa, D.|author4=Ryans, R.|date=2008|title=Quantitative studies of the optical and UV spectra of Galactic early B supergiants. I. Fundamental parameters|journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics|volume=481|issue=3|pages=777\u201397|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20077125 |bibcode=2008A&A...481..777S |arxiv = 0801.4289 }}</ref> Analysis of the spectra and age of the members of the Orion OB1 association yields a mass 34.6 times that of the Sun ({{solar mass|40.8}} on the [[main sequence]]) and an age of 5.7 million years.<ref name=\"Voss 2010\">{{cite journal|author= Voss, R.|author2= Diehl, R.|author3= Vink, J. S.|author4= Hartmann, D. H.|date=2010|title=Probing the evolving massive star population in Orion with kinematic and radioactive tracers|journal= Astronomy and Astrophysics|volume=520|pages=10|id=A51 | doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201014408|bibcode=2010A&A...520A..51V|arxiv = 1005.3827 }}</ref>\n\nA more recent detailed analysis of Alnilam across multiple wavelength bands produced very high luminosity, radius, and mass estimates, assuming the distance of 606 [[parsec]]s suggested by the Hipparcos new reduction.<ref name=hipparcos/> Adopting the larger parallax from the original Hipparcos reduction gives a distance of 412 parsecs<ref name=perryman>{{cite journal|bibcode=1997A&A...323L..49P|title=The HIPPARCOS Catalogue|journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics |volume=323|pages=L49|last1=Perryman|first1=M. A. C.|last2=Lindegren|first2=L.|last3=Kovalevsky|first3=J.|last4=Hoeg|first4=E.|last5=Bastian|first5=U.|last6=Bernacca|first6=P. L.|last7=Cr\u00e9z\u00e9|first7=M.|last8=Donati|first8=F.|last9=Grenon|first9=M.|last10=Grewing|first10=M.|last11=Van Leeuwen|first11=F.|last12=Van Der Marel|first12=H.|last13=Mignard|first13=F.|last14=Murray|first14=C. A.|last15=Le Poole|first15=R. S.|last16=Schrijver|first16=H.|last17=Turon|first17=C.|last18=Arenou|first18=F.|last19=Froeschl\u00e9|first19=M.|last20=Petersen|first20=C. S.|date=1997}}</ref> and physical parameters more consistent with earlier publications. The luminosity of {{solar luminosity|832,000}} at 606 parsecs is the highest ever derived for this star.<ref name=\"puebla\">{{cite journal|author=Puebla, R.E. |author2=Hillier, D.J. |author3=Zsarg\u00f3, J. |author4=Cohen, D.H. |author5=Leutenegger, M.A.|date=2015|title=X-ray, UV and optical analysis of supergiants: \u03f5 Ori|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=456|issue=3|pages=2907\u20132936|doi=10.1093/mnras/stv2783 |bibcode=2016MNRAS.456.2907P|arxiv = 1511.09365 }}</ref>\n\nAlnilam's relatively simple spectrum has made it useful for studying the [[interstellar medium]]. Within the next million years, this star may turn into a [[red supergiant]] and explode as a [[supernova]]. It is surrounded by a [[molecular cloud]], [[NGC 1990]], which it illuminates to make a [[reflection nebula]]. Its [[stellar wind]]s may reach up to 2000 [[velocity|km/s]], causing it to lose [[mass]] about 20 million times more rapidly than the Sun.<ref name=\"crowther\" />\n\n== Nomenclature and history ==\n''\u03b5 Orionis'' is the star's [[Bayer designation]] and ''46&nbsp;Orionis'' its [[Flamsteed designation]].\n\nThe traditional name ''Alnilam'' derives from the [[Arabic]] \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0638\u0627\u0645 ''al-ni\u1e93\u0101m'' 'arrangement/string (of pearls)'. Related spellings are ''Alnihan'' and ''Alnitam'':<ref name=allen>{{Cite book |first=Richard Hinckley |last=Allen |title=Star-names and their meanings |date=1936 |pages=314\u2013315 }}</ref> all three variants are evidently mistakes in transliteration or copy errors, the first perhaps due to confusion with \u0627\u0644\u0646\u064a\u0644\u0645 ''al-nilam'' '[[sapphire]]'.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The name of epsilon Orionis|last=Knobel |first=E. B.|journal=The Observatory |volume=32 |page=357|date=September 1909|bibcode=1909Obs....32..357K}}</ref> In 2016, the [[International Astronomical Union]] organized a [[IAU Working Group on Star Names|Working Group on Star Names]] (WGSN)<ref name=\"WGSN\">{{cite web | url=https://www.iau.org/science/scientific_bodies/working_groups/280/ | title=IAU Working Group on Star Names (WGSN)|accessdate=22 May 2016}}</ref> to catalog and standardize proper names for stars. The WGSN's first bulletin of July 2016<ref name=\"WGSN1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/WGSN_bulletin1.pdf | title=Bulletin of the IAU Working Group on Star Names, No. 1 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> included a table of the first two batches of names approved by the WGSN; which included ''Alnilam'' for this star. It is now so entered in the IAU Catalog of Star Names.<ref name=\"IAU-CSN\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/IAU-CSN.txt | title=IAU Catalog of Star Names |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Orion's Belt===\n{{Main article|Orion's Belt}}\nThe three belt stars were collectively known by many names in many cultures. Arabic terms include ''Al Nij\u0101d'' 'the Belt', ''Al Nasak'' 'the Line', ''Al Alk\u0101t'' 'the Golden Grains or Nuts', and, in modern Arabic, ''Al M\u012bz\u0101n al H\u2022akk'' 'the Accurate Scale Beam'. In [[Chinese mythology]], they were also known as The Weighing Beam.<ref name=allen/> \n\nIn [[Chinese astronomy|Chinese]], {{lang|zh|\u53c3\u5bbf}} ({{lang|zh-Latn|Sh\u0113n S\u00f9}}), meaning ''[[Three Stars (Chinese constellation)|Three Stars]] (asterism)'', refers to an asterism consisting of Alnilam, [[Alnitak]], and [[Mintaka]] (Orion's Belt), with [[Betelgeuse]], [[Bellatrix]], [[Saiph]], and [[Rigel]] later added.<ref>{{in lang|zh}} ''\u4e2d\u570b\u661f\u5ea7\u795e\u8a71'', written by \u9673\u4e45\u91d1. Published by \u53f0\u7063\u66f8\u623f\u51fa\u7248\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8, 2005, {{ISBN|978-986-7332-25-7}}.</ref> Consequently, the [[Chinese star names|Chinese name]] for Alnilam is {{lang|zh|\u53c3\u5bbf\u4e8c}} ({{lang|zh-Latn|Sh\u0113n S\u00f9 \u00e8r}}, {{lang-en|the Second Star of Three Stars}}).<ref>{{in lang|zh}}  [http://aeea.nmns.edu.tw/2006/0605/ap060525.html AEEA (Activities of Exhibition and Education in Astronomy) \u5929\u6587\u6559\u80b2\u8cc7\u8a0a\u7db2 2006 \u5e74 5 \u6708 25 \u65e5]</ref> It is one of the western mansions of the [[White Tiger (Chinese astronomy)|White Tiger]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Stars and planetary systems in fiction#Alnilam (Epsilon Orionis)|Alnilam in fiction]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{APOD |date=29 September 2009 |title=Image of Alnilam}}\n\n{{Stars of Orion}}\n\n{{Sky|05|36|12.8|-|01|12|06.9|800}}\n\n[[Category:Bayer objects|Orionis, Epsilon]]\n[[Category:B-type supergiants]]\n[[Category:Flamsteed objects|Orionis, 46]]\n[[Category:Orion (constellation)]]\n[[Category:Stars with proper names]]\n[[Category:Alpha Cygni variables]]\n[[Category:Durchmusterung objects|BD-01 0969]]\n[[Category:Henry Draper Catalogue objects|037128]]\n[[Category:Hipparcos objects|026311]]\n[[Category:HR objects|1903]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alnilam"}
